{{Infobox person
| name        = Richard Plunz
| nationality = American
| alma_mater  = [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]]
| occupation  = [[Architect]]
| notable_works = ''A History of Housing in New York City'' (1990)<br/>''Two Adirondack Hamlets in History'' (1999)<br/>''Turgutreis 1974'' (2016)
}}

'''Richard Plunz''' is an American architect, critic, and historian. He is Professor of Architecture at the [[Columbia Graduate School of Architecture, Planning and Preservation|Graduate School of Architecture, Planning and Preservation]] at [[Columbia University]] [[New York City|in the City of New York]] and the Founder and Director of the [[Urban Design Lab]], a research unit of Columbia's [[The Earth Institute|Earth Institute]], where he also serves as Professor.<ref>GSAPP faculty profile https://www.arch.columbia.edu/faculty/53-richard-plunz</ref>

== Education and career ==
Plunz studied architecture at [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] in [[Troy, New York]], where he earned [[Bachelor of Science|B.S. in engineering]], [[Bachelor of Architecture|B.Arch]], and [[Master of Architecture|M.Arch]] degrees. There, and at [[Pennsylvania State University]], he researched [[urban history]] and [[urban planning|development]] and began developing field techniques related to the anthropology of building and people's relationship to the built environment.<ref>Urban Design Lab profile http://urbandesignlab.columbia.edu/our-team/richard-a-plunz/</ref>

He has been at [[Columbia University|Columbia]] since 1973, and served as Chair of the Division of Architecture and Director of the post-professional Urban Design Program from 1992 to 2015. Plunz has also held visiting professor positions at the [[KU Leuven|Catholic University of Leuven]], in [[Flanders]], and [[Polytechnic University of Turin]], in [[Italy]].<ref>Design Trust profile http://designtrust.org/people/fellows/richard-plunz/</ref>

== Research and publications ==
Plunz has pursued research related to housing, [[urban history]], [[anthropology]], [[Parametricism|urban parametrics]], and design. During the 1970s, he undertook anthropological field research in a serious of major studies using digitized environmental modeling to help understand the divergent urban contexts of [[Mantua, Philadelphia|Mantua]], in [[West Philadelphia]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://search.lib.virginia.edu/catalog/u540004|title=Mantua Primer: Toward a Program for Environmental Change {{!}} Pennsylvania State University}}</ref> the ''[[frazione]]'' of [[San Leucio]] in [[Southern Italy]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/2015945|title=San Leucio: vitalità d'una tradizione: traditions in transition {{!}} Pennsylvania State University}}</ref> and in the [[Adirondack High Peaks]] region in [[New York (state)|New York State]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/two-adirondack-hamlets-in-history-keene-and-keene-valley/oclc/43095901|title=Two Adirondack hamlets in history: Keene and Keene Valley {{!}} Purple Mountain Press}}</ref>

Other significant work includes a 40-year study in [[Turgutreis]], [[Turkey]], which documented the transformation of small villages into a modern city through the experiences of 15 families,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dr.com.tr/Kitap/Turgutreis-1974-Ingilizce-/Suha-Ozkan/Foreign-Languages/Reference/Architecture-Decoration-Desing/urunno=0000000708529|title=Turgutreis 1974 {{!}} Literatur Yayincilik}}</ref> and a [[Millennium Cities Initiative]]-developed strategic analysis of [[Accra|Accra, Ghana]]'s Ga Mashie and Nima neighborhoods.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://urbandesignlab.columbia.edu/projects/green-and-sustainable-infrastructure/urban-development-in-accra-ghana-an-implementation-toolkit|title=Urban Development in Accra, Ghana: an Implementation Toolkit {{!}} Urban Design Lab}}</ref>

His ''A History of Housing in New York City'' tracks [[New York City|the city]]'s housing developments from 1850 and was published in 1992,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cup.columbia.edu/book/a-history-of-housing-in-new-york-city/9780231062978|title=A History of Housing in New York City {{!}} Columbia University Press}}</ref> and republished in 2016 with new research and an introduction by [[urban historian]] [[Kenneth T. Jackson]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/dual-histories-home-ownership-nyc/|title=A House Divided: The Dual Histories of Home Ownership in NYC {{!}} The Brian Lehrer Show}}</ref> [[Urban planner]] [[Peter Marcuse]] wrote of the book in a 1992 review, “For its wealth of information and description, for its humane perspective, and for the illumination it provides on the role of architecture in the shaping of housing in New York City over the decades, this is a most valuable book.” <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marcuse|first=Peter|date=1992|title=Plunz, Richard 1990: A history of housing in New York City: dwelling type and social change in the American metropolis. New York: Columbia University Press.|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1468-2427.1992.tb00178.x|journal=International Journal of Urban and Regional Research|volume=16.2|pages=333–334|via=}}</ref>

== Awards ==
Plunz received the [[Andrew J. Thomas|Andrew J Thomas]] Award from the [[American Institute of Architects]] for his pioneering work in housing.<ref>American Institute of Architects, New York Chapter, Awards Archive https://www.aiany.org/architecture/awards-archive/</ref>

